body: What version of MLflow is the docker container (tracking server) configured to use? Is it latest or did you pin it to 1.21.0?

> What version of MLflow is the docker container (tracking server) configured to use? Is it latest or did you pin it to 1.21.0?

It's pinned to 1.21.0.

I also checked the MySQL database entries and nothing seems off. Frankly, I am puzzled why the mlflow sdk shows this behavior. SDK version is `mlflow~=1.21.0` (mlflow, version 1.21.0) as well according to my requirements.txt.
Thanks for clarifying @tahesse . We'll try to get a repro going to see if we can figure out what might be going on.

@BenWilson2 I just set up a fresh mlflow installation and encountered the exact same issue. Could it be the case that the error stems from `mlflow.pytorch.log_model`?

The artifact Uri prints: `s3://<bucket-name>/mlflow/1/a951531a7a31422c938dab6a1e24f396/artifacts`

Hi @tahesse could you run this and confirm that the 2nd tuple return value is `'mlflow/1/a951531a7a31422c938dab6a1e24f396/artifacts'` ?

``` python
from mlflow.store.artifact.s3_artifact_repo import S3ArtifactRepository
S3ArtifactRepository.parse_s3_uri(<your artifact uri>)
```
@BenWilson2 It dissects `s3://<bucket-name>/mlflow` into `("<bucket-name>", "mlflow")`. What does it mean that the experiment id + run id is missing in the second entry of the tuple?

it means something is very broken with how urllib is parsing your uri. If I put a 'fake' uri in like this:

``` python
S3ArtifactRepository.parse_s3_uri("s3://my-bucket-mlflow/mlflow/1/a951531a7a31422c938dab6a1e24f396/artifacts")
>> ('my-bucket-mlflow', 'mlflow/1/a951531a7a31422c938dab6a1e24f396/artifacts')
```

It's preserved just fine. Without seeing what your bucket name is, I can't really figure out why it's not parsing yours properly.

It might help troubleshooting if you put your artifact uri directly into: 

``` python
import urllib

urllib.parse.urlparse(<your artifact uri>)
```
to see what the parsed elements are. 

For example, the uri parsing from the above example returns:

``` python
ParseResult(scheme='s3', netloc='my-bucket-mlflow', path='/mlflow/1/a951531a7a31422c938dab6a1e24f396/artifacts', params='', query='', fragment='')
```

If your netloc value is not present (which is what I think is happening because of some unparseable syntax) that might lead us down to coming up with a fix for this.
@tahesse would you be ok sharing the bucket name with us on slack? mlflow-users.slack.com

Also, could you do a double-check on what your server env config is for ``${AWS_S3_URL}`` just to make extra certain that it's:
`export AWS_S3_URL="s3://<bucket>"`
and not 
`export AWS_S3_URL="s3:///<bucket>"`

with an additional "/" this will definitely give the behavior that you're seeing.

@BenWilson2 The bucket name is `product-mlflow-bucket` whereas product is our internal product name. Just lowercase characters. The S3 url starts with `s3://`. I even hard-coded it to make sure that is not the issue.
I wonder if a change in S3 configuration may cause this issue, because this is really everything that changed before it showing this behavior.
does this behavior still happen if you create a new experiment and log new runs to it after the s3 config change?

@BenWilson2 Pardon, in my previous post I was running
`S3ArtifactRepository.parse_s3_uri('s3://product-mlflow-bucket/mlflow')` which did yield the tuple I mentioned atop.

If I run 
```python
S3ArtifactRepository.parse_s3_uri("s3://my-bucket-mlflow/mlflow/1/a951531a7a31422c938dab6a1e24f396/artifacts")
```
I receive
```python
('my-bucket-mlflow', 'mlflow/1/a951531a7a31422c938dab6a1e24f396/artifacts')
```
as an output.

This behavior also shows for pre-existing experiments and for new experiments. It is consistently broken after the S3 credential change on all experiments.

I found that when I remove the `mlflow` folder from the `s3://my-bucket-mlflow/mlflow` and redeploy it does save the artifacts to `s3://my-bucket-mlflow/mlflow/my-bucket-mlflow/<experiment-id>/<run-id>/artifacts`. I am not sure if this hints to a misconfiguration on the S3 side. We had multiple iterations on that one and didn't found anything odd.

Edit: The urllib parsing did go through as one would expect.
I ran
```python
import urllib
print(urllib.parse.urlparse("s3://my-bucket-mlflow/mlflow/1/a951531a7a31422c938dab6a1e24f396/artifacts"))
```
and got 
```python
ParseResult(scheme='s3', netloc='my-bucket-mlflow', path='/mlflow/1/a951531a7a31422c938dab6a1e24f396/artifacts', params='', query='', fragment='')
```
